<section id="about">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head"><span class="tag-num">01</span><h2>About the Project</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">
      Most robot grippers struggle with one thing: handling objects of very different sizes and shapes with the same gripper. A gripper built for small objects usually fails on large ones, and vice versa. SPIROB solves this by being able to grip things ranging from tiny objects to ones 260 times its own body weight — all with the same simple design, no need to swap parts or motors.

      Nature already solved this problem. Animals like octopuses, elephants, and chameleons grab objects using flexible, curling limbs (tentacles, trunks, tails) instead of rigid pincers. Researchers noticed these body parts all follow the same curve in math — called a logarithmic spiral — and built a robot using that exact shape.
    </p>
    <div class="about-grid">
      <div>
        <p>
        </p>
      </div>
